{
  "id": "colours",
  "order": 2,
  "title": {
    "en": "Colours",
    "uz": "Ranglar"
  },
  "icon": "🎨",
  "blurb": "Name the colours — and meet the famous ko'k",
  "article": [
    {
      "heading": "The word for colour is rang",
      "body": [
        "**Rang** means \"colour\". You will see it stuck onto other words: *jigarrang* (liver-colour = brown), *kulrang* (ash-colour = grey). Colours work like ordinary adjectives and go **before** the noun, with no agreement to worry about: *qizil olma* (a red apple), *qizil olmalar* (red apples) — the colour word never changes."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "uzbek": "qizil gilam",
          "english": "a red carpet"
        },
        {
          "uzbek": "oq non",
          "english": "white bread"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "heading": "The famous ko'k",
      "body": [
        "The one colour to watch is **ko'k**. Today it usually means **blue** — the colour of the sky and of Samarqand's tiled domes. But traditionally it also covers fresh **green**: green tea is **ko'k choy**, and *ko'kat* means leafy greens. The modern, unambiguous word for green is **yashil**.",
        "So if someone offers you *ko'k choy*, they mean green tea, not blue tea!"
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "uzbek": "ko'k osmon",
          "english": "the blue sky"
        },
        {
          "uzbek": "ko'k choy",
          "english": "green tea (literally \"ko'k tea\")"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
